english:
  title: Memorial Requesting Donations for the Restoration of Taoist Temples Below the City
  author: Choe Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: "The Purple Extremity Palace seeks to restore the various Taoist temples situated below the city, and requests donations of tiles, timber, and other materials. \n\nHumbly considered: In苦縣, the sage Laozi was born, and in the Middle Kingdom he expounded the Way. His true nature is the ancestor of our sage dynasty; we honor it by the grand name of the Source of the Supreme Way. Like jade leaves and golden branches, his luminous shade shines through ten thousand ages. Like precious vessels and jade repositories, his subtle teachings are transmitted to the four directions. Thus ritual observances found their home, and sacred ceremonies never fell into disuse. The divine palace and sacred halls perfectly mirror the celestial realms; the secret sanctuaries and consecrated altars are solemnly established as blessed grounds.\n\nOur region, blessed with the elegant customs of Eastern Wu and the heroic power of southern Yan, has known worthy scholars—those like 鮑 who celebrated eloquence in their writings, and those like 揚 who cautioned against vanity in their compositions. Yet few pursue the Supreme Way with diligence, and fewer still guard the Mysteries with care. What seems profound becomes cause for laughter; what demands reverence falls into neglect. Thus the halls of blessing are overgrown with weeds, the chambers of immortals crumble beneath wind and rain.\n\nIn these times of calamity—when ominous cries echo and venomous strikes threaten—we see only the swift dispatch of urgent military orders; we hear only the weary thunder of armored cavalry. As the world grows turbulent, silence deepens the teachings.\n\nYet if opportunity for restoration comes, surely the conditions for generosity are not absent. Now, fortunately, we encounter the Grand Commandant, whose virtue flows like the dragon, whose Way runs deep with radiance. Versed in the mysteries known to 黃石公, called by all an Imperial Teacher; awaiting the visitation of 赤松子, he ventures forth with six subtle stratagems to subdue all chaos, and within, practices the nine transformations of inner cultivation. In stillness, he sweeps away the dust of battle; in leisure, he contemplates the sun and moon of another realm. He honors the three luminaries and perfects the vital breath through devoted practice. Behold how his true rank ascends and auspicious omens multiply—colored clouds drift on Chu's mountain winds, and black cranes cry toward the moon above隋宮.\n\nPreviously, the bandits of the Long River threatened the south; in past years, the northern tribes pressed from淮's banks. Yet through the Grand Commandant's heroic might, the multitudes of evil were scattered. The four neighbors trust in him as they did in 齊桓公; the eight provinces are grateful as they were to 邵父. We see the farmers working their fields, hear songs rising to heaven. The ancients said: \"Do what must be done when it must be done.\" \n\nFor the restoration of these temples below the city, we now gather skilled craftsmen to expand and beautify the ancient grounds, fashioning halls of gold and silver that shine with radiance, so that all who follow the Way may keep their conduct pure. Should this modest work succeed, may our worthy vows bear fruit—may the imperial vision shine forth in renewed glory, and may valiant troops forever crush the great bandits.\n\nOur second prayer is this: May the Grand Commandant's stratagems surpass those of 張良, his leisure pursuit exceed that of 范蠡. Where horse-tracks have turned to dust and phoenix songs echo from the towers, when flowers bloom on the Isles of Immortals, may he ride the white deer in spring's drunken ease; when rains pass over fields of sacred fungi, may he at dawn entrust his plow to the azure ox, content to set aside minor verses and dwell in the vast longevity of the Great Cyclus. Then, from the winged creatures above to the swimming creatures below, may all sentient beings receive boundless blessing.\n\nYet the temples, long abandoned and decayed, require vast resources we cannot provide alone. We rely upon the collective merit of all donors. The Buddha teaches that one should gladly give what is difficult to give; the Tao teaches that such giving flows naturally. We trust you will not rashly promise what cannot be kept.\n\nRespectfully submitted."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Purple Extremity Palace' (紫極宮) refers to a Taoist temple dedicated to the highest principle of cosmology in Daoist theology.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'six subtle stratagems' (六奇) and 'nine transformations' (九轉) are classical Daoist and military-philosophical concepts representing mastery of both external affairs and internal cultivation.
  - key: ''
    value: References to Huang Shigong (黃石公), Red Pine Master (赤松子), and immortal figures draw upon legendary Daoist and Confucian sage traditions.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'three luminaries' (三光) refer to the sun, moon, and stars—celestial bodies revered in Daoist cosmology.
